nderful “play,” the frank and eager expression of the oblique muscles and the “smile” of her navel—to borrow from the vocabulary of the belly dancer’s art.

One day he brought his shaving kit along and helped her to get rid of all three patches of body hair:

“Now I’m Scheher,” he said, “and you are his Ada, and that’s your green prayer carpet.”

Their visits to that islet remained engraved in the memory of that summer with entwinements that no longer could be untangled. 